<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18471122-252">
               <interp inst="t18471122-252" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18471122"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18471122-252" type="date" value="18471122"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18471122-252-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-252-18471122 t18471122-252-offence-1 t18471122-252-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>252. <persName id="def1-252-18471122" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-252-18471122" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-252-18471122" type="surname" value="DAY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-252-18471122" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">RICHARD DAY</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18471122-252-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18471122-252-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18471122-252-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="fraud"></interp>, for obtaining, by false pretences, 50 earthenware pipes, value 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. the goods of <persName id="t18471122-name-1409" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1409" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1409" type="surname" value="DOULTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1409" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18471122-252-offence-1 t18471122-name-1409"></join>Henry Doulton</persName> and another.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1410" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1410" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1410" type="surname" value="DOULTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1410" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY DOULTON.</persName>
                  </hi> I am partner with my father, we are potters, at High-street, Lambeth. In consequence of a communication, in August, I went to Victoria-road—the prisoner and Marson, who was convicted last Sessions, came there soon after—Marson said he required 600 pipes, the value of which was about 70<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. for a sewer he was about to build—(there was a sewer being built)—he introduced me to the prisoner, as the ground-landlord of the pro<lb></lb>perty through which the sewer was to pass—he had said in the counting-house that the ground-landlord would be there; and when I got there, he said, "This is Mr. Day"—Marson walked a little way, and took me to another part, and then we returned to Day—we went into the Builders' Arms, and there Day gave me a written guarantee—it was handed to Jury on the trial of Marson, and I never saw it again.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. COOPER.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was it produced by yourself, or the attorney? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> by me—I have not made inquiries here for it—I am quite certain as to the words of it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> He said the prisoner was the ground-landlord? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—the prisoner represented himself as the ground-landlord—Marson said, "Mr. Day, some gentlemen have been here to inquire the rent of your land, and I named a sum"—Day said that was quite right—Day was repeatedly referred to as the owner of the land—Day told me Marson was a very respectable man, he had known him a long while—he asked Marson how many pipes he would want—he said about 600—Day said, "Then, Mr. Doulton, you will send some over in the morning"—I sent one load next morning, it was the 24th or 25th Aug., by Stimpson, to the amount of 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—in conse<lb></lb>quence of what Stimpson said, I did not send any more—I wrote to Day—he had given me his address, "Richard Day, Esq., Eltham"—he replied by a letter, which I have here, in answer to mine—(<hi rend="italic">read</hi>—"Eltham, 6th Sept. Gentlemen—I did not know the pipes were delivered; but I shall see Mr. Marson on the subject, when he will write you, and make a settlement when the contract is completed")—I have not received any money for the pipes I sent—I am not prepared to state that I should not have parted with the pipes, through Day had not guaranteed it.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184711220234"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. COOPER.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you known Marson before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—he was the principal speaker—he met me there alone—I think it is very likely. considering the circumstances, knowing that it was done under the Kennington Union, that I should have sent the materials, supposing Day had taken no part; but the guarantee was an additional security—in the conversation in the Builders' Arms, Marson said, "Mr. Day, some persons have been here inquiring the value of your land, what you let it at per house," referring to this very land—be said, "About your land here"—I cannot swear that the word "here" was used, but he referred to that land—I have heard that Day has banked, but rather disreputably—this letter is my writing (<hi rend="italic">looking at one</hi>)—in this I applied to Day for the money—I know that he lived at Elt✗—the solicitor who sits by you, called once on me—I did not on that occasion agree to wait for the money—I said I had been out of town, or I should have prosecuted Day before—-the solicitor said the money would be paid very likely that day—I said I would not wait longer than that day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1411" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1411" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1411" type="surname" value="STIMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1411" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT STIMPSON.</persName>
                  </hi> I am carman to Mr. Doulton. On 26th Aug. I car<lb></lb>ried a load of fifty pipes from my master's to Victoria-road—I saw a sewer going on—I asked for Mr. Marson—he was not there—I went further, and inquired, but he was not there—I brought the pipes back to Victoria-road—I saw Mr. Marson there—he said to me, "Where have you been? you have been to the wrong place"—I said, "No"—I delivered the pipes at Victoria-road—Marson received them, and signed my bill, which was handed up here last Session—I heard something, and I communicated it to my master.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Were there men working there? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, at the sewer in Victoria-road, and the other sewer too.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1412" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1412" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1412" type="surname" value="COCKBURN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1412" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT COCKBURN.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a stone-mason, at Marlborough-road, Chelsea. On 26th or 27th Aug. I was asked if I knew any one who would by some pipes—I took fifty pipes from Victoria-road, where they were making a drain, to Mr. Thirst, in Cadogan-street, Chelsea—4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 19<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. was paid for them—Marson got two men to help me load—I saw the prisoner about the 15th Sept., I think—I told him I had heard that he and Marson had received some pipes under false pretences at a potter's some where at Lambeth, and I in<lb></lb>tended to go on to Marson and ascertain what it was—he said, "If you go there you will transport me, and think of my wife and child, what are they to do?"—I said, "You did not think of me"—I went on to Marson's, found Mr. Doulton, and went there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Had you known Marson before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, he was a joiner and builder—I had known Day a few months—Marson told me Day was an independent gentleman, living at Eltham—he brought him to my house, and said, "This is the gentleman that is going to advance me some money towards building"—when I spoke to Mr. Day, he did not say I was wrong—he flew in a passion, and said, "If you go there you will transport me"—I did not speak to policeman—I went to Mr. Doulton's—he said he was busy, and could, not attend to it; when he could he would send me a letter and let me know.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did Marson bring Day to you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About June of July.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1413" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1413" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1413" type="surname" value="THIRST"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1413" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD THIRST.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a builder. On 27th Aug. I bought fifty drain<lb></lb>pipes of Marson for 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 19<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—Mr. Doulton saw them two or three days afterwards, and owned them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1414" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1414" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1414" type="surname" value="DOULTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1414" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY DOULTON</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I saw the pipes at Mr. Thirst's—they were what were sent to Marson.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How came you to part with your pipes? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Marson and day</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184711220235"></xptr>
               <p>being together, and Marson saying Day was the ground-landlord, and Marson stating in his presence that he was building a sewer, and had the contract for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1415" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1415" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1415" type="surname" value="WILLIAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1415" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL WILLIAMS.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a carman and a contractor—my brother and myself were contractors for that sewer that was building in Victoria-road, Kensington—I know Marson—he had nothing to do with building the sewer—we took the ground of Mr. Vallotton.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1416" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1416" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1416" type="surname" value="VALLOTTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1416" type="given" value="THEODGRE JAMES"></interp>THEODGRE JAMES VALLOTTON.</persName>
                  </hi> I live at 2, Hyde-park—my father is the ground-landlord of the ground on which this sewer was built in Victoria-road—I do not know Day—he has nothing to do with that land.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Does not Mr. Barry claim that land? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not know—he claims all Kensington—the land on which the palace is built he claims.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1417" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1417" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1417" type="surname" value="GOFF"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1417" type="given" value="CHARLES BURGESS"></interp>CHARLES BURGESS GOFF</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant, L</hi> 8.) I took the prisoner in White Hart-court, Drury-lane—I passed him first, and from the description I had I believed him to be the man—I turned and said, "Good morning, Mr. Day"—he said, "Good morning"—I said I wanted him for being concerned with Marson in obtaining pipes from Mr. Doulton—he said, "You must have been planted on me"—he wanted to go to his solicitor—I took him to the station, and found on him this letter—(<hi rend="italic">produced.</hi>)</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">This letter was signed Richard Day, but bore no direction; it contained allusions to Marson, and mentioned his being in Horsemonger-lane gaol.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Day gave you his address? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I went to Eltham for him, and found he had lived at a shoe-maker's shop there—I found a banker's receipt, which I produce.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18471122-252-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
